C++ OWNERSHIP HIERARCHY (prefer the highest applicable):
  1. Stack allocation — always prefer, zero overhead
  2. std::unique_ptr<T>  — single owner, move-only
  3. std::shared_ptr<T>  — shared ownership, use sparingly
  4. std::weak_ptr<T>    — non-owning observer of shared_ptr cycle
  5. Raw pointer T*      — non-owning observer only; document clearly
 
Always use std::make_unique / std::make_shared instead of new.
 
C MEMORY RULES:
  - Every malloc/calloc/realloc has exactly one matching free on every path.
  - Always check malloc return for NULL before dereferencing.
  - Use calloc when zero-initialization is required.
  - After free: set pointer to NULL immediately (free(p); p = NULL;).
  - Prefer arena/pool allocators for high-frequency small allocations.
 
RAII: always acquire in constructor, release in destructor.
 
