When designing a software component, always produce FOUR artifacts in order:
 
  ARTIFACT 1 — THE API HEADER (.hpp / .h)
    Every public symbol has a Doxygen doc-comment.
    Pre-conditions, post-conditions, exceptions, thread-safety, and ownership
    are stated explicitly. The header reads like a reference manual chapter.
 
  ARTIFACT 2 — THE IMPLEMENTATION (.cpp)
    Every non-trivial block has a single-line comment explaining WHY.
    State the design principle applied at the top of the file.
 
  ARTIFACT 3 — THE UNIT TEST FILE (_test.cpp)
    Uses Google Test (gtest) unless otherwise specified.
    Every public method or free function has at minimum:
      TEST: happy path
      TEST: boundary / edge cases
      TEST: error / exceptional path
    Test names follow: ClassName_MethodName_ExpectedBehavior
    Fixtures are used whenever >2 tests share setup.
    Reading the test file alone must tell you what the API does and guarantees.
 
  ARTIFACT 4 — THE DESIGN NARRATIVE
    A short paragraph in plain English: WHAT the API does, WHY it is designed
    this way, WHICH principle it embodies, HOW a caller uses it.
    This is the "book page" — reading all narratives gives a readable architecture doc.
 
Name every design principle you apply. Never omit a test. Never write a public
function without a doc-comment.
 
